<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTD/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<!--
    Hardened-runtime entitlements for Roost.app.

    Effective when the bundle is code-signed (ad-hoc or Developer
    ID). The M8-era bundle.sh signs ad-hoc with the `runtime`
    option; Phase 8 adds Developer ID + notarization on top.

    File is intentionally a near-empty plist: Roost doesn't need
    additional capabilities beyond what the hardened runtime
    grants by default for a forkpty-spawning AppKit app.

    What we INTENTIONALLY do not need:

    * `cs.disable-library-validation` — would only be needed if
      we `dlopen`-ed third-party signed dylibs (e.g. plugins
      signed by another team-id). We don't. The embedded
      `roostctl` is exec'd (forkpty path → execve), and execve
      is governed by Gatekeeper / quarantine, not library
      validation. Sub-agent review flagged the earlier inclusion
      of this entitlement here as based on a misreading of the
      docs.

    * `cs.allow-unsigned-executable-memory` / `cs.allow-jit` —
      libghostty-vt is linked as a static archive (its code is
      part of Roost's own signed image), no JIT, no dynamically
      generated machine code at runtime. Add `allow-jit` only if
      a future Ghostty bump introduces a JIT path (e.g. font
      shaping via SIMD codegen).

    * `network.client` / `network.server` — Roost does not speak
      over a network socket. The IPC server is UNIX-domain only.

    * App Sandbox flags — sandboxing the shells Roost spawns
      would defeat the product. cmux makes the same choice.

    If a future change requires a real entitlement, drop the
    intentional-emptiness comment block and add it.
-->
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
</dict>
</plist>
